#Text=Fateh Shah
#Text=Fateh Shah was the king of Garhwal , a small kingdom in North India , from 1684 to 1716 . [ 1 ]
#Text=Campaigns
#Text=H. G. Walton states that Fateh Shah led an attack from Dehradun on Saharanpur in 1692 .
#Text=The attack was repelled by Sayyed Ali , the Mughal imperial general . [ 2 ]
#Text=According to research by G.R.C. Williams , Fateh Shah established a township called Fateh Pur in Haraura Pargana of Saharanpur . [ 3 ]
#Text=According to Rahul Sankrityayan and Fateh Prakash , Raja Fateh Shah also invaded Tibet , where his sword and armour were preserved in the monastery at Daba for a long time . [ 3 ]
#Text=Battle of Bhangani
#Text=Main article : Battle of Bhangani
#Text=Dabral and Bhakt Darshan believe that Fateh Shah invaded Sirmur in 1692 .

#Text=Ajay Singh Rawat writes that the year of invasion mentioned by these writers is not correct , and the animosity between Fateh Shah and Raja of Sirmur is the prelude to the Battle of Bhangani ( 1688 ) . [ 3 ]
#Text=Mat Prakash ( or Medni Prakash ) , the Raja of Sirmur sought the help of Guru Gobind Singh to reconcile his differences with Fateh Shah .
#Text=The Guru persuaded Fateh Shah to restore good relations with the Raja of Sirmur and to return the seized portion of the Sirmur kingdom .
#Text=In 1688 , the marriage of Fateh Shah 's daughter was arranged with the son of Raja Bhim Chand of Bilaspur ( Kahlur ) .
#Text=Guru Gobind Singh had sent jewellery worth one lakh rupees to Fateh Shah 's daughter at the time of marriage ceremony .
#Text=However , Bhim Chand had grown wary of the rising influence of Guru Gobind Singh , and had developed animosity toward the Guru .
#Text=He threatened to cancel the marriage if Fateh Shah accepted the gift from the Guru . [ 3 ]
#Text=Later , the combined forces of Bhim Chand and Fateh Shah launched an attack on Guru Gobind Singh 's camp .
#Text=Guru Gobind Singh was already prepared for a battle , and the two forces met at Bhangani , located about six miles from Paonta , on 18 September 1688 .
#Text=Dr. Fauja Singh believes that the Battle of Bhangani should not be connected with the story of Fateh Shah 's refusal of the wedding presents sent by the Guru . [ 3 ]
#Text=The author of Bichitra Natak does n't mention the name of Raja Bhim Chand , and states that Fateh Shah fought with him for no obvious reasons . [ 3 ]

#Text=According to Ajay Singh Rawat , one of the possible grievances of Fateh Shah could have been the presence of Guru 's armed camp near his territory ; Paonta was a strategic location on the only convenient route connecting Nahan ( capital of Sirmur ) and Garhwal .
#Text=He also believes that it is likely that the subjects of Garhwal suffered from " lawless activities " of some of the Guru 's followers . [ 3 ]
#Text=These reasons could have led him to ally with Bhim Chand to attack the Guru .

#Text=According to the author of Bichitra Natak , and majority of historians , the battle resulted in the victory of the author 's ( i.e. the Guru 's ) forces , and the enemy forces fled from the battlefield .

#Text=However , authors such as Pandit Harikrishna Raturi , Anil Chandra Banerjee and A. S. Rawat believe that the battle ended without any consequences , since the Guru 's victory is not substantiated by any territorial annexations , and the Guru entered into an understanding with Bhim Chand soon after the battle . [ 3 ] [ 4 ]
#Text=Although , there is practically no evidence about the territorial ambitions of the Guru .
#Text=Battles with Kumaon
#Text=Fateh Shah also fought several battles against Kumaon , without any conclusive results .
#Text=Gyan Chand of Kumaon , who ascended the throne in 1698 , raided Pindar valley in Garhwal after he was crowned .
#Text=In 1699 , he crossed Ramganga river and plundered Sabli , Khatli , and Sainchar .
#Text=Fateh Shah replied by invading Chaukot and Giwar areas of Kumaon in 1701 .
#Text=In 1703 , the Kumaonis defeated the Garhwalis in the battle of Duduli ( near Melchauri in Garhwal ) .
#Text=In 1707 , the Kumaon forces annexed Juniyagarh in Bichla Chaukot , and razed the old fort at Chandpur .
#Text=Raja Jagat Chand of Kumaon plundered Lohba and garrisoned the fort of Lohbagarh .
#Text=Next year , he proceeded as far as Srinagar in Garhwal .
#Text=According to H. G. Walton , Raja of Kumaon occupied Srinagar , and Fateh Shah fled to Dehradun . [ 2 ]
#Text=Fateh Shah appears to have returned very soon to Garhwal ; in 1710 , he mobilized his troops in Badhan .
#Text=Patronage to art and literature
#Text=The contemporary writings mention Garhwal as a very prosperous state during Fateh Shah 's reign . [ 3 ]
#Text=Fateh shah was a great patron of art and literature .

#Text=Like Vikramaditya and Akbar , he is said to have nine illustrious figures ( Navaratnas ) in his court : Sureshanand Barthwal , Revatram Dhasmana , Rudridutt Kimothi , Hari Dutt Nautiyal , Vasvanand Bahuguna , Shashidhar Dangwal , Sahdev Chandola , Kirit Ram Khanthola , and Hari Dutt Thapliyal . [ 3 ]
#Text=Some of the encomiastic works from Ratan Shah 's period include :
#Text=Fateh Shah Karna Granth by Jatadhar ( or Jatashankar )
#Text=Fateh Prakash by Ratan Kavi ( or Kshem Ram )
#Text=Vrit Vichar by Kavi Raj Sukhdev Misra
#Text=Vrit Kaumudi or Chhandsar Pingal by Mati Ram
#Text=Ratan Kavi 's eulogies state that there was perfect law and order in Garhwal during Fateh Shah 's reign , and people did not lock their houses as a result .
#Text=Kavi Raj Sukhdev Misra praises the Raja 's gallantry .
#Text=Mati Ram 's Vrit Kaumudi compares the Raja 's generosity with that of the Maratha king Shivaji .

#Text=Ananda Coomaraswamy mentions that two painters from the Mughal court , Shyam Dass and Har Dass , accompanied Suleiman Shikoh to Garhwal ; it is possible that these painters got patronage during the reign of Fateh Shah , which resulted in the birth of the Garhwali school of painting .
#Text=Family
#Text=Fateh Shah had five children : [ 1 ]
#Text=Upendra Shah ( became the Raja after his father 's death )
#Text=Dalip Shah
#Text=Madhukar Shah
#Text=Pahar Shah
#Text=A daughter who married Rajkumar ( later Raja ) Ajmer Chand , the son of Raja Bhim Chand of Bilaspur ( Kahlur ) .
